<pre>

<h1 class="text-primary">SIMD Parallelism</h1><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIMD" target="_blank" class="btn btn-success">SIMD wiki</a>

GPUs ~ thousands of cores
  - Good example of SIMD
  - Static Partioning
  - Chunks of programs
    * fixed fork-join size
  - limited instruction set
    * no indirect memory --> no pointers
  + graphics
  - used for same calculation on multiple data --> factoring prime numbers
  - CUDA - framework for gpu programming
    * <a href="http://www.nvidia.com/object/cuda_home_new.html" class="btn btn-info btn-xs" target="_blank">CUDA (nvidia)</a>

<h2 class="text-success">Heterogenus Parallelism</h2>

FPGAs
  - <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field-programmable_gate_array" class="btn btn-warning btn-xs" target="_blank">FPGA wiki</a>
    * 'most certain thing to happen in programming' (hp)
  - FPGA vs ASIC
    * ASIC programmed once
    * FPGA 'field programmable'

Liquid Metal (lime) <a href="http://researcher.watson.ibm.com/researcher/view_project.php?id=122" class="btn btn-primary btn-xs" target="_blank">LIME</a>
  - language designed for heterogenus programs

'Parallel programming in the next 10 years - heterogenus parallelism'

